abstract = {This chapter addresses the complex issue of assessing soil erosion and sediment transport rates. First, the basic concepts and involved processes are presented and defined. Second, a brief explanation of the role played by the spatial and temporal scales introduces the list of direct (e.g., measurement of changes in soil level, splash devices, runoff collectors, gauging stations, sediment traps in streams) and indirect (e.g., sediment tracers, sediment cores and bathymetry) methods used to obtain onsite measurements and the usefulness of numerical approaches (e.g., empirical and process-based models, indices, machine learning techniques) to calculate and map the spatially distributed hydrological response of the soil. Third, two case studies in agricultural areas with permanent crops (olive groves) in southern Spain and three hydrological basins of different sizes (small, medium, and large ones) in north-eastern Spain are presented as case studies. Final remarks and current challenges close the text.}
